Recently, I have been thinking a lot on how my approach to solve hard tasks compares to my approach to solve difficult logic puzzles\footnote{According to the \href{https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/puzzle}{Cambridge dictionary}, \textit{a puzzle is a situation that is difficult to understand or a problem or question that you have to answer by using your skill or knowledge}. Well, this pretty much also describes an hard task right? QED, you can stop reading!}. Both actions have a lot of things in common with each other. For example, both seem daunting at first sight, and yet, despite all of this, if you are anything like me you are more inclined to do one versus the other...

Before further unraveling this thread, a \textit{disclaimer}. This text represents my perspective on both the world and my psyche. There are no guarantees that you share the same experience as me or that the few tips provided here will help you in your tasks or puzzle solving affairs. Nevertheless, I decided to share it in the offchance that it may entertain or even help someone.

\subsection{Introduction}

For someone who rarely solves puzzles and never deals with non routine tasks, the prospect of having to do so might be paralyzing. Any preexisting motivation quickly fades away when faced with the road ahead. After all, \textit{the road isn't even paved}, and we have to pave it ourselves to reach our destination.

To do so, I find it helpful to divide the process of solving a puzzle into \textit{three different phases}:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The \textbf{Initial State}, where we think carefully about the given initial data;
    \item The \textbf{End State}, where we think carefully about the end goal;
    \item The \textbf{The Middle}, where the \textit{magic} happens.
\end{itemize}

The ordering might seem strange at first sight, with the \textbf{End State} coming before \textbf{The Middle}. The reason for this is that we often think about the solution even before we try to actually solve the puzzle. This is not problematic, in fact this thought process can be quite informative and even influence our first steps towards a solution! Let us analyze carefully each one of these phases from the point of view of solving a Sudoku puzzle. Afterwards, I will present an examination of the different phases when solving an hard\footnote{The notion of difficulty is subjective and heavily depends on the individual experiences of every one of us. The choice of this particular mathematical problem is not important. What matters is that the presented approach is present in the process of solving the problem.} mathematical problem.
