\subsection{The Middle}

How do you go from start to end? Obviously, you play the game! But if you're new at this, you may enter a state of despair. "What do you mean \textit{play the game}?", "Where do I start?", you may ask yourself. And that is where \textbf{experience} comes into the picture.

An \textbf{experienced solver} may take a quick glance at a puzzle and instantly identify three or four interesting parts of the puzzle to attack. Yes, attack! \textbf{It's you versus the puzzle}! The \textbf{experienced solver} not only has an arsenal of techniques to apply to the puzzle, he also has experience on using them and familiarity with most of the constraints. An \textbf{experienced solver} has solved so many puzzles that this one is just one more, the puzzle does not scare him. To a newbie, seeing the \textbf{experienced solver} solve the puzzle seems almost magical, the leaps he makes with such a seemingless effort. Ah... Anyways, to solve hard puzzles, \textbf{we should aim to become an experienced solver}.

You know how one becomes an \textbf{experienced solver}? \textit{By solving puzzles.} Easy, medium, hard, it does not matter, the experienced solver has solved them all! The leaps he makes now seem effortless, but behind them are countless hours exploring the constraints, trying and retrying assumptions, defying puzzles time and time again.
There was a time where the \textbf{experienced solver} was a newbie. And surely there are puzzle types where the \textbf{experienced solver} is a newbie! No one can solve everything in this world. But the \textbf{experienced solver} is aware of that. He knows what being a newbie takes, the toll one has to pay to move forward.
If you are a newbie, the road ahead is not easy. \textbf{You must be resilient!} You should not be scared of trying even though you may fail. For if you do not try, you will forever be a newbie.

Here are some actionable tips I have found helpful to keep in mind:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Do not despair. Even if you do not see any point of attack, start small. Take one of the constraints and see if you can use it in an area of the puzzle with a lot of clues. Didn't work? Take another constraint, take both at the same time! \textbf{Keep trying!}
    \item Make sure you understand the constraints and what they imply! Make a few sanity checks or sketches of the constraint in action. This helps a lot in memorizing both the constraint and its implications. With time, you will start noticing patterns, these patterns become techniques in your arsenal. The next time you meet this constraint you already have some prior experience to help you. \textbf{You no longer have to start from zero!}
    \item Even if you meet a new, never before seen constraint, you now have experience in being a newbie! Yes! By being a newbie several times, you start to get used to it. When meeting a new puzzle that has some similarities to others you are already experienced on, you no longer fret. \textbf{You become aware and learn to enjoy the process!}
\end{itemize}

The advice in this section may be a little discouraging. Unfortunately, there is no \textit{magic trick} or \textit{shortcut} here\footnote{If there is, please contact me immediately!}. \textbf{The Middle} is the part where we actually do most of the work. The best advice really is \textbf{to do}. If, after some effort, one is still blocked, then maybe there is an easier puzzle with these constraints that we can solve\footnote{\href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_P%C3%B3lya}{Pólya} is often attributed with saying, \textbf{“If you can't solve a problem, then there is an easier problem you can solve: find it.”} It is good advice.}.

A friend of mine a couple of years ago said a phrase that really stuck with me. \begin{equation*}\text{Iterate, iterate, iterate.}\end{equation*} Only by constant iteration, pondering clues and constraints, may we solve the puzzle. 
Only by constant iteration, one square at a time, will we solve the puzzle. 
Only by constant iteration, a little bit at a time, can we improve ourselves, towards becoming an \textbf{experienced solver}. 

It is only by iterating this process of trial and failure that we gain experience. \textbf{Fail now so that you will not fail in the future.}

